content.text:
The likely culprit is the view transitions in `layout-main.webc:70-78`:

```css
@view-transition {
  navigation: auto;
}
::view-transition-old(root),
::view-transition-new(root) {
  animation-duration: 0s;
}
```

Even with `animation-duration: 0s`, the browser still runs the full view transition lifecycle — snapshot the old page, navigate, render the new page, snapshot it, then run the (instant) transition. The page is frozen during that snapshot/render phase, which creates that brief "dead" moment where scrolling and clicks don't respond.

The render-blocking head script and the component JS are both lightweight, so those shouldn't be the issue.

If you want to confirm, you could temporarily comment out the `@view-transition` block and see if the stutter goes away.

You're right. Let me look more carefully at what's missing.

You're setting `animation-duration: 0s` on `::view-transition-old(root)` and `::view-transition-new(root)`, but there's also a `::view-transition-group(root)` pseudo-element that handles size/position animation between the old and new page states. It has a default duration of 250ms. If the pages differ in height or scroll position, that group animation is still running for a quarter second while the page is frozen.

Try adding the group to your selector:

```css
::view-transition-old(root),
::view-transition-new(root),
::view-transition-group(root) {
  animation-duration: 0s;
}
```

